{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 13:10:17.383817", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report — Clos EBGP Fabric\nSummary\n- Control plane (BGP) appears healthy and converged across the observed FRR routers: super-spine, spines and leaves show established BGP sessions and consistent prefix counts.\n- Data-plane / host-level issue: pc_0_1 is not running (container stopped) and therefore unreachable. Its leaf (leaf_router_0_1) still has the 10.0.1.0/24 interface and advertises the prefix via BGP, so routing looks correct but the host itself is down.\n- No evidence of router interface administratively down or BGP session flaps in the collected outputs. Routing tables contain the expected connected /24s and remote /24s.\n\nEvidence and Findings (by device)\n1) leaf_router_0_0\n- Interfaces: eth4 = 10.0.0.1/24 (connected host network). Several spine-facing /31 addresses (172.16.0.33, .41, .49, .57) are up.\n- Routing: shows local 10.0.0.0/24 and remote 10.0.[1..3].0/24 via next-hops on 172.16.0.x links.\n- BGP (show ip bgp summary): local AS 65200, 4 neighbors; each neighbor session is Up and reporting PfxRcd=7 / PfxSnt=8. This is consistent with this leaf advertising its connected /24 (sends 8) and receiving the other 7 remote /24s from peers.\n\n2) leaf_router_0_1\n- Interfaces: eth4 = 10.0.1.1/24. Spine-facing /31s up.\n- Routing: local 10.0.1.0/24 present, remote 10.0.[0,2,3].0/24 reachable via BGP.\n- BGP: local AS 65201, 4 neighbors; all sessions Up; PfxRcd=7 / PfxSnt=8 (same pattern as leaf_router_0_0).\n\n3) spine_router_0_0 and spine_router_0_1\n- All listed spine-facing interfaces are Up with /31 addresses.\n- BGP:\n  - spine_router_0_0 (AS 65100) shows 6 neighbors (2 super-spine neighbors + 4 leaf/other neighbors). Sessions Up and peer PfxRcd values show super-spines advertising 8 prefixes and leaves advertising fewer prefixes; overall consistent.\n  - spine_router_0_1 (AS 65101) similarly shows all peers Up and stable.\n\n4) super_spine_router_0\n- Multiple /31 links up to spines; BGP summary shows 8 neighbors (various spine ASes) and sessions all Up; PfxRcd values consistent (super-spine sees 4 prefixes from each spine shown).\n- Routing table entries show next-hops for 10.0.* via spine nexthops — BGP routes present.\n\n5) pc_0_0 and pc_0_1 (hosts)\n- pc_0_0: 10.0.0.2/24 present, default route via 10.0.0.1 (leaf). Container responded to config queries; no traffic (RX/TX counters zero), but network config is present.\n- pc_0_1: container not running — attempts to query interfaces/route returned an error (\"container ... is not running\"). No IP/route output available.\n\nAnomalies / Abnormal Behavior\n1) Host offline: pc_0_1 is down (container not running). This is the only clear “faulty” element from the collected data. The leaf (leaf_router_0_1) still has the 10.0.1.1 interface and advertises 10.0.1.0/24 via BGP, so routing plane still carries the prefix even though the host itself is offline. Symptom: host-level service outage (host unreachable), but network routing appears to be functioning.\n\n2) Topology descriptor mismatch (observational)\n- The initial textual topology listed two spine routers and a single super-spine. The observed BGP neighbor lists and interface IPs indicate more inter-router adjacencies (neighbors with IPs such as 172.16.0.48, .56, .50, .58, etc.). In other words, the running network appears to include more spine/leaf adjacencies or additional routers than the minimal topology description. This is not a network failure but is an inconsistency between the provided topology description and the actual observed neighbor addressing — important for inventory / documentation accuracy.\n\nWhat is functioning normally\n- All BGP sessions that were queried are in the Established state (Up), with sensible prefix counts exchanged. No peers show long OutQ/InQ, no BGP error states reported in the outputs gathered.\n- Router interfaces used for inter-router links show UP/LOWER_UP and have /31 addresses assigned.\n- Routing tables on routers show connected /24s and learned remote /24s via expected next-hops. The control plane is converged for the prefixes present.\n\nRoot-cause analysis (for the observed outage)\n- Symptom: pc_0_1 unreachable / no interface data.\n- Root cause: the host/container pc_0_1 process is not running (docker container not running). The leaf router still has the 10.0.1.0/24 interface and advertises the network via EBGP, so routing is not preventing reachability — the host endpoint itself is offline. Evidence: exec attempts to pc_0_1 returned docker/container not running error; leaf_router_0_1 shows the 10.0.1.1 interface (so the leaf will advertise the prefix even without an active host).\n\nAdditional notes\n- Because leaves advertise their connected /24 regardless of host presence, BGP visibility of the prefix does not guarantee host reachability. This is exactly the situation here: network-level routing is healthy but the endpoint is down.\n- If the intent of the topology check was to validate there are exactly the routers in the textual description, there is a mismatch: BGP neighbors and next-hop addresses indicate more adjacencies than those explicitly listed in the short topology description. That should be documented as an inventory/topology mismatch (not a routing fault).\n\nConclusion\n- Control plane (BGP routing) across observed routers is healthy and converged.\n- The only confirmed anomaly is at the host layer: pc_0_1 is not running (container stopped), causing the host-level outage. Routing propagates the prefix (the leaf advertises 10.0.1.0/24), so the root cause for host unreachability is the host/VM/container itself being down rather than a routing or forwarding failure.\n- There is an ancillary documentation/topology inconsistency: observed neighbor IPs indicate more adjacencies than the minimal topology supplied.\n\nIf you want, I can (upon your instruction) run additional checks such as:\n- Attempting pings from leaves/spines to the host IPs to confirm reachability at L3.\n- Show detailed FRR BGP table entries (show ip bgp) for particular prefixes to verify next-hop propagation.\n- Re-run host/process checks or start pc_0_1 container (only if you request mitigation/repairs).", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 17451, "output_tokens": 3785, "total_tokens": 21236, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 16896}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2240}}}
